The Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE) entry CWE-296 describes the weakness of a product failing to properly validate the chain of trust for a digital certificate back to a trusted root certificate. This results in incorrect trust of resources associated with that certificate. Certificates rely on a chain of trust from the root certificate authority to establish authenticity. If any link in this chain is not properly validated, the certificate loses its trustworthiness as an identity metric. Attackers can exploit this to spoof trusted entities or access sensitive information. Proper implementation of certificate validation, including revocation checks and confirmations of signature validity, is crucial to preserve confidentiality and integrity. 

# Summary bullet points

* CWE-296 deals with improper validation of a certificate's chain of trust, enabling spoofing or unauthorized access
* Certificates rely on a chain of trust back to a reputable root certificate authority to confirm authenticity 
* If any link in the chain of trust is not properly checked, the certificate can't be trusted
* Consequences include spoofed entities, unauthorized access, loss of confidentiality and integrity
* Proper certificate verification requires validating all signatures, revocation status, constraints and extensions
* Certificate pinning increases risk if relevant certificate properties aren't fully checked before pinning

